==Personal life==
Irvine is noted for his "[[Hipster (contemporary subculture)|hipster]]" persona off the pitch, and his support for social justice causes, especially LGBTQ inclusion in soccer.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lynch |first=Joey |date=2024-01-09 |title=Meet Australia's Jackson Irvine, soccer's hipster king |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/39262960/meet-australia-st-pauli-jackson-irvine-soccers-hipster-king |access-date=2026-03-06 |website=ESPN.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Millar |first=Colin |date=2025-05-12 |title=Australia’s Jackson Irvine ‘disappointed’ by men’s football’s reaction to English ban on transgender women |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6349706/2025/05/12/irvine-fa-transgender-ban-women/ |access-date=2026-03-06 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Snape |first=Jack |date=2023-09-08 |title=Socceroo Jackson Irvine: ‘We want to use the game as a driving force for good’ |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/sep/09/socceroo-jackson-irvine-interview-aus-vs-mexico- |access-date=2026-03-06 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

Since April 2024 Irvine has been hosting his own radio show called ‘Heimspiel’ every four weeks on the Hamburg music station [[ByteFM]].<ref>https://www.phonostar.de/radio/bytefm/live/heimspiel/s/8227</ref>

